The Economics of Violence
COPENHAGEN – What is the greatest source of violence in our world?
Brutal conflicts in Syria, in Ukraine, and elsewhere are constantly in the news, and therefore many would probably say war.
But that proves to be a great mistake.
The correct answer plays a role when we want to find cost-efficient solutions for this and other global problems.
It goes without saying that everyone would gladly end war and violence, just as we would gladly put an end to poverty, hunger, and global warming and ensure access to education for all people.
However, due to limited resources, there are limits to what the international community can do.
We need to set priorities, and for that, an economic cost-benefit analysis can be used.
The international community is working on new development goals for the next 15 years, and the Copenhagen Consensus has asked some of the world's leading economists to assess which goals, in their view, would be the wisest.
Is the goal of reducing violence worth the use of means that could otherwise, for example, be used in the fight against hunger?
And, if so, which forms of violence should be targeted?
According to a study by James Fearon from Stanford University and Anke Höffler from the Center for the Study of African Economies at the University of Oxford, violence in society—murders and, above all, violence against women and children—poses a far greater problem than civil wars.
For every death on the battlefield of a civil war, nine people die due to interpersonal violence, and for every two combatants who die, one child is killed.
In 2008, 418,000 people were killed worldwide, and far too many countries record murder rates of more than 10 victims per 100,000 inhabitants, which the World Health Organization refers to as an epidemic.
A single murder in America costs one person's life and society 9.1 million US dollars.
Measured against the global national income, this form of violent crime alone costs 1.7% of the global gross social product (GDP).
Of course, this is not a direct financial loss for the world economy, but rather a way to express the consequences.
If murder could be abolished, societies around the world would be better off in a way that could be measured as 1.7% of GDP.
Compare this with the significantly lower costs of civil wars, which amount to about 0.2% of global GDP.
That is, however, still much less than the largest source of violence altogether: violence against women in the home.
Based on studies published in the scientific journal Science, 28% of all women in sub-Saharan Africa experienced violence from their partners or family members in the past year.
Among these are women who were beaten, forced into early marriages, subjected to sexual violence, became victims of crimes committed in the name of "honor," and underwent female genital mutilation.
According to a cautious estimate, the societal costs of violence by intimate partners amount to 4.4 trillion US dollars or 5.2% of global GDP.
The second largest source of violence is the maltreatment of children, which is committed by parents in 80% of cases.
The definition of what constitutes child abuse varies from culture to culture, but approximately 15% of children experience each month what the UN refers to as severe physical punishment.
These include punches to the face, head, or ears, and a quarter of these children are repeatedly hit as hard as possible with an object.
This suffering affects about 290 million children every month.
The social costs amount to $3.6 trillion or 4.2% of global GDP.
Only a tiny fraction of international aid funds is currently being used to reduce violence in society and improve criminal justice systems.
The enormous costs borne by society and individuals cry out for action.
Unfortunately, there are still hardly any reliable insights as to where the limited resources should best be used.
All that can be said is that the money spent to reduce violence could be used more effectively.
Large sums of aid are allocated to "fragile states" to help end or prevent civil wars, yet only 0.27% of international aid goes to projects with the component of "crime prevention."
Other programs can certainly contribute indirectly, but obviously, much could be improved.
Some solutions, as is clear, work very well.
More effective social institutions can reduce violence against children.
Studies in the U.S. state of Washington have shown that home visits by trained staff can reduce child abuse, improve children's quality of life and their physical and mental health, and lower the costs of care and legal proceedings.
A dollar spent on this program produces a benefit worth 14 US dollars: it is therefore an extremely cost-effective measure.
In many cases, the societal attitude must change.
To reduce violence against women and girls, a program called SASA! in Uganda is working.
(Swahili for "Now!") to spread the idea that violence in partnerships is unacceptable and has contributed to halving the number of cases.
That is a fantastic result, even though there is no analysis of cost efficiency available.
There are examples from other countries where effective measures are being taken.
In 1993, there were 80 murders per 100,000 inhabitants in Bogotá.
With a comprehensive approach—including a time limit on alcohol sales, reclaiming public space, and improvements in the police and judicial systems—the murder rate was reduced to 21 victims per 100,000 inhabitants in the year 2004.
That is still a high number, but far below Detroit's murder rate of 55 victims per 100,000 residents.
Alcohol plays a role in many physical attacks, and the findings from Bogotá suggest that controlling its availability could be of significant importance.
In the United Kingdom, a pilot study on the better enforcement of existing regulations showed that violent attacks could be reduced in a very cost-efficient manner, with the benefits outweighing the costs by a ratio of 17 to 1.
Although we still do not know enough, two points are clear: First, domestic violence against women and children imposes annual costs on society amounting to 8 trillion US dollars, thus presenting a huge—yet far too little noticed—global problem.
Secondly, there are solutions that can help address some of these problems in a very cost-effective manner.
For this reason, reducing domestic violence belongs to the shortlist of priorities for the next global development goals.
